\begin_layout Standard
Status consumption was notably elaborated by Veblen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 in his 1899 treatise titled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Theory of the Leisure Class
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Around the time when Marx had endorsed a view of all commodities as products
 of labour (diamond and corn alike), Veblen has explored the psychological
 basis for consumption among the economic classes.
 At times, his view of status consumption may appear critical of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bourgeois
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wastefulness 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Throughout the entire evolution of conspicuous expenditure, whether of goods
 or of services or human life, runs the obvious implication that in order
 to effectually mend the consumer’s good fame it must be an expenditure
 of superfluities.
 In order to be reputable it must be wasteful.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 - but Veblen hardly dwells upon the equivalence of labour for exchange
 of commodities.
 While he marks the tendency amongst the elite to distance themselves from
 physical labour - he argues that this tendency has transformed itself into
 a desire of displaying exploits and has survived in the culture from more
 primitive hunter-gatherer and agrarian societies.
 This symbolism - he argued - is inherent in all exchange of goods and services
 (including devotion and education 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The adoption of the cap and gown is one of the striking atavistic features
 of modern college life, and at the same time it marks the fact that these
 colleges have definitely become leisure-class establishments, either in
 actual achievement or in aspiration.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 ).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assisted with the developments in game theory and an improvement in the
 quality of microdata from consumption surveys, an interest in Veblen's
 observations has been revived in the recent years (see Frank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond,FrankModel"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Hirsch 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Koustobinas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 We argue that this recent attention to status consumption need not to be
 viewed asunder from the consumer demand literature on habit-formation (see
 for example Muellbauer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MuellbauerRationalityMyopia1988."
literal "true"

\end_inset

's discussion of the myopia amongst consumers and Fisher-Shell
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FisherShell1968"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for the classical treatment of quality and cost-of-living indices).
 Using the intertemporal framework with life-cycle assumptions, one could
 view status consumption as an inertia in moving away from a state of higher
 quality - a tendency that may in turn depend on the long-term characteristics
 such as social identity or education.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relevance of social identities in consumption habits has been a theme
 visited by much of the literature in conspicuous consumption (see Chao
 et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chao1998"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Charles et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CharlesHurstRace"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Omori et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "OmoriSmithVisRace"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Kaus
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\series bold
 
\series default
and Khamis et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 The literature in marketing studies has similarly explored identity formation
 with acquired goods.
 A model that views consumption in the context of a ranking order based
 on income or wealth, could be used to endogenise the role of social identity
 in conspicuous consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion of status most commonly used in literature is one where it is
 one of the long-term characteristics of the consumer.
 This allows the studies in sociology and health sciences to use status
 as simply a vector eduction or income (see Michelson et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Psake et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PsakiSeidman2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a few examples).
 Using such a definition for status consumption poses a certain parardox
 - if status was only accumulated over a sufficiently long-term, how can
 there be any utility from status consumption in an intertemporal framework?
 This seeming paradox however is easily resolved when one considers that
 status is subject to change with consumption - just the way it is shaped
 by income or education.
 This is the widely accepted view of status provided by Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who view status as an income-based ranking order that can be altered by
 the consumer with consumption.
 In other words, a consumer achieves status utility through status consumption
 by moving herself up in a ranking order that is otherwise determined by
 wealth and income.
 This is the view that we use in our intertemporal formulation of status
 consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of developing economies, this view raises some fundamental
 questions on whether the status goods in a developing country should be
 the same as those that are considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

visible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the developed economies or not.
 As the relative wealth differences are more relevant for status differences
 in the developing countries, the wealth differences could have far more
 weight for status than the limited range of visible items available to
 a consumer in the developing world (where industrial development is concentrate
d into fewer urban areas).
 We find that the presence of wealth differences in the developing countries
 is not always given its due attention in much of the literature on conspicuous
 consumption we have surveyed (except for some studies directly exploring
 the effect income inequality on conspicuous consumption with exogenously
 observed poverty/income levels or GINI indices - see Jaikumar 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Chai et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Some studies, we find, include long-term durable goods (e.g.
 housing) in status-related consumption while others choose to focus on
 non-durable consumption.
 We believe that an intertemporal substitution approach - which explicitly
 considers the role of wealth differences on status - could help us assess
 whether the particular long-term durable goods should be viewed as part
 of status consumption in an economy or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indeed the presence of social segregation or varied social identities poses
 another issue with the identification of visible consumption - a problem
 less tractable than the differences in wealth levels.
 Social segregation may imply that the status competitions to reach the
 upper classes are also segmented.
 Thus the very idea of pecuniary emulation which Veblen defines (i.e.
 that the lower economic classes tend to emulate the habits of past upper
 economic classes - whose context in the developing world has been expolored
 in the literature - see Timothy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) - ought to be refined based on the importance of one's own reference group
 in status competitions (see Frank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Chai
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the empirical arguments for this refinement).
 Since status competitions are relevant only in one's own reference group,
 the social identities would also influence status consumption within their
 respective corresponding reference groups - much the way wealth differences
 do.
 This is unlikely to be a serious empirical issue in most cases since social
 segregation is often a result of long-term economic differences, but the
 concern that we wish to highlight is that the effect of social identities
 and wealth difference on status consupmption may not necessariliy be aligned.
 A reference group that is poor in absolute terms may not offer better means
 to indicate status but it may offer a pool of smaller fishes - i.e.
 a lower reference point for status utility which the consumer intends to
 maximise.
 Therefore, despite the transformation of consumer markets due to rapid
 industrialisation in many developing countries - where the income differences
 have narrowed and new markets for status have been created (see Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 , Ustuner-Holt
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UstunerHolt2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 , Burke 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Wisman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WismanSavingClassIdentity2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), the prevalent socio-economic inequalities could still have far more weight
 than the consumption of a few conspicuous items that are considered visible
 in the developed economies ( see Ustuner-Holt
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UstunerHolt2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for criticism of a certain 
\shape italic
belle epoque 
\shape default
view of status consumption and Khamis et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for how visibility surveys are adjusted for unequal economies 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The questions in the consumer survey 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 (which is how a researcher may obtain the list of visible items) is adjusted
 to include items that may indicate wealth.
 This is because the criteria of what items are of visible importance is
 not enough for identifying status consumption in an environment where wealth
 differences are both wide and visible.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The combined effect of social differences and wealth differences on status
 is the quantitative concern that motivates our model for status-related
 consumption.
 If status is viewed as a ranking order based on long-term characteristics
 such as income, education then a certain acquired characteristics and consumpti
on may be seen as a way to offset the deep wealth and social hierarchies
 which determine the ranking (see Corneo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 For the empirical analyses, the wealth in a developing economy can be proxied
 relatively easily with the stock of durable goods the consumer has (inclusive
 of housing, land and other long-term assets).
 The contribution of non-durable consumption to status - on the other hand
 - is only through the quality of non-durable consumption.
 This is because the fulfillment of basic needs cannot offer any advantage
 in a status competition.
 A consumer with a habit of 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
high-quality in consumption (or deriving higher felicity above the fulfillment
 of needs) would 
\shape italic
ceteris paribus 
\shape default
have higher status than another consumer consuming less quality.
 Therefore as long as a common set of consumer needs - which are fundamentally
 the same by definition - can be measured in the population being observed,
 there is no status utility to be achieved through addressing of needs themselve
s.
 This has a particular implication for our model of utility - if there is
 any status related utility to be derived from non-durable consumption,
 it would be constituted in the felicity from 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
quality (which is defined as distance from needs which themselves are observed
 within a particular reference group).
 It also follows that any status that is not signaled with quality in non-durabl
e consumption or is associate with innate social characteristics of the
 consumer it must come out of the possession of (utility from) long-term
 durable goods (i.e.
 the proxy of wealth)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To incorporate life-cycle assumptions, we consider a durable long-term only
 if it can be passed on by the consumer to the next generation.
 These determine the long-term demands of the consumer while her short-term
 concerns (which could themselves be influenced by the acquired wealth)
 comprise only of needs and quality (inclusive of short-term durable items
 - if any).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A robust empirical measure of quality has been subject to much debate in
 the litearture owing largely to the lack of sufficiently detailed consumption
 surveys.
 Most consumption surveys hardly record the market-observed prices or the
 quantities of the items consumed - let alone the brand-related details
 of the items.
 This makes the identification of higher quality difficult.
 The market-prices of items purchases or even quantities consumed - which
 could permit us to view quality as the proportion of expensive items standardis
ed by quantity (see Nelson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Deaton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Gibson et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GibsonKimQualityBog2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and McKelvey 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McKelveyQuality2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) - if recorded, tend to be limited to food items alone.
 Noting the absence of quantities consumed and the detaied prices of key
 diary items, we use the notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

excess
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 quality by consider a higher-than-required consumption based on a minimum
 necessary consumption (this is similar to the problem of cost-of-living
 indices in the literature - see Fisher 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FisherShell1968"
literal "false"

\end_inset

for the classical approach to the problem).
 We thus observe how the cost of a standard basket of basic needs varies
 across the regions and districts in the economy and infer the varying cost
 of needs as the basis of our measure for quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As long as the basic needs of the consumer in an economy can be determined,
 the measure of quality is simply the expenditure in 
\shape italic
excess 
\shape default
of the cost of needs.
 An empirical assessment of what is consider 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

necessary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the population of consumers is therefore key to our definition of quality
 - much as it is for the very definition of conspicuous consumption 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Encyclopaedia Britannica definition of conscpicious consumption provides
 an illustrative instance of the role that empirical judgment play in determinin
g consumer needs : 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Conspicuous consumption ...
 describes and explains the practice by consumers of using goods of a higher
 quality or in greater quantity than might be considered necessary in practical
 terms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BritannicaConspCons2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 The sticking point then becomes the determination and measurement of the
 needs themselves.
 Here too, the idea that all of us have a set of basic needs has not been
 without controversies.
 On one hand, we have the view that needs are determined solely by subjective
 preferences (see Townsend
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) while on the other, there is the view that a common man's needs can supersede
 her subjective interests (wants).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our own empirical analyses, we lean towards an objective middle-path
 proposed by Doyal and Gough
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 who consider autonomy itself - in addition to health - as a basic need
 of the consumer without shunning the idea that the needs across cultural
 contexts should be standardised.
 The basic needs of the consumer are thus the standard requirements not
 meeting which would lead to a definite harm (this is in accordance to the
 theory argued for by Doyal and Gough 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 To an argument that a family can survive on just starch, for example, the
 counter-argument would be that a foreseeable damage to the health of the
 consumer incurred by not having other nutrients is definite.
 A starch diet fulfilling the set of dietary needs can thus be ruled out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ideas of health and autonomy may be slightly abstract but could roughly
